{"id":"1909.10570","submitter":"Yann-Meing Law-Kam Cio","authors":"Yann-Meing Law and Jean-Christophe Nave","title":"FDTD schemes for Maxwell's equations with embedded perfect electric\n  conductors based on the correction function method","comments":"40 pages, 15 figures, modification of Acknowledgments","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work, we propose staggered FDTD schemes based on the correction\nfunction method (CFM) to discretize Maxwell's equations with embedded perfect\nelectric conductor (PEC) boundary conditions. The CFM uses a minimization\nprocedure to compute a correction to a given FD scheme in the vicinity of the\nembedded boundary to retain its order. The minimization problem associated with\nCFM approaches is analyzed in the context of Maxwell's equations with embedded\nboundaries. In order to obtain a well-posed problem, we propose fictitious\ninterface conditions to fulfill the lack of information, namely the surface\ncurrent and charge density, on the embedded boundary. Fictitious interfaces can\ninduce some issues for long time simulations and therefore the penalization\ncoefficient associated with fictitious interface conditions must be chosen\nsmall enough. We introduce CFM-FDTD schemes based on the well-known Yee scheme\nand a fourth-order staggered FDTD scheme. Long time simulations and convergence\nstudies are performed in 2-D for various geometries of the embedded boundary.\nCFM-FDTD schemes have shown high-order convergence.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Sep 2019 18:50:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 Jul 2020 19:47:44 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 29 Jul 2021 20:10:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-02"}
{"id":"1909.10571","submitter":"William Worden Jr","authors":"Neil R. Hoffman, Christian Millichap, and William Worden","title":"Symmetries and hidden symmetries of $(\\epsilon, d_L)$-twisted knot\n  complements","comments":"Removed some highlighting of text that was overlooked in the previous\n  version. This is the final version, to appear in Algebraic & Geometric\n  Topology. 38 pages, 15 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":"Algebr. Geom. Topol. 22 (2022) 601-656","doi":"10.2140/agt.2022.22.601","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we analyze symmetries, hidden symmetries, and commensurability\nclasses of $(\\epsilon, d_L)$-twisted knot complements, which are the\ncomplements of knots that have a sufficiently large number of twists in each of\ntheir twist regions. These knot complements can be constructed via long Dehn\nfillings on fully augmented links complements. We show that such knot\ncomplements have no hidden symmetries, which implies that there are at most two\nother knot complements in their respective commensurability classes. Under mild\nadditional hypotheses, we show that these knots have at most four\n(orientation-preserving) symmetries and are the only knot complements in their\nrespective commensurability classes. Finally, we provide an infinite family of\nexplicit examples of $(\\epsilon, d_L)$-twisted knot complements that are the\nunique knot complements in their respective commensurability classes obtained\nby filling a fully augmented link with four crossing circles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Sep 2019 18:51:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 Jan 2021 21:38:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 1 Mar 2021 18:49:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-10"}
